P&G Stock Price Prediction using Monte Carlo Simulation¶

In this project, we aim to predict the future price of PG stock over the next 1000 days. We use a Monte Carlo simulation, a computational algorithm that relies on repeated random sampling to obtain numerical results.

Data Acquisition and Preparation¶

In this section, we're going to import the necessary libraries and download the historical data for the PG stock.

Calculating Daily Returns¶

In this section, we calculate the daily returns using the formula np.exp(drift.values + stdev.values * norm.ppf(np.random.rand(t_intervals, iterations))). This formula takes into account the drift (the direction of the stock price) and the standard deviation (the volatility of the stock price).

  1. Setting up Time Intervals and Iterations
In [20]:
t_intervals = 1000 # forecasting the stock price for the comming 1000 days
iterations = 10 # produce 10 predections of the stock
$$ daily\_returns = e^{r} $$$$ r = drift + stdev \cdot z $$
  1. Calculating Daily Return
In [21]:
daily_return = np.exp(drift.values + stdev.values * norm.ppf(np.random.rand(t_intervals, iterations)))
                                                                        #the intercals and iterations mean create
                                                                       #10 predections for each coming 1000 days

$$ S_t = S_0 \mathbin{\cdot} daily\_return_t $$


$$ S_{t+1} = S_t \mathbin{\cdot} daily\_return_{t+1} $$


$$...$$

$$ S_{t+999} = S_{t+998} \mathbin{\cdot} daily\_return_{t+999} $$

  1. Running the Simulation
    In this section, we run our simulation using a loop that iterates over our time intervals. For each iteration, we calculate a possible future stock price and store it in our price_list.
In [25]:
for t in range (1, t_intervals):
    price_list[t] = price_list[t-1] * daily_return[t]

Plotting the Predicted Values¶

In this section, we plot the 10 predicted stock price paths over the next 1000 days. This will give us a visual representation of our Monte Carlo simulation.

In [27]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15,8))
plt.plot(price_list)
plt.title('Monte Carlo Simulation of P&G Stock Price Over 1000 Days')
plt.xlabel('Days')
plt.ylabel('Simulated Price')
plt.show()
  1. Plotting the Mean Prediction
    In this section, we calculate and plot the mean of our 10 predicted stock price paths over the next 1000 days. This will give us a single prediction path that represents the average outcome of our simulations.
